Urbanspace  Union Square is a newish addition--adding a small food hall to Union Square.  open from morning to night. the interior is clean, plenty of seating, and well-maintained. there are ~ a dozen eateries...many familiar ones like Bob White Counter, Pita Yeero, and Summer Salt to name a few. most of the spots offer abridged menus versus their complete menus at stand-alone locations. if you need variety of choices, this Urbanspace location  will serve your needs well. i have stopped by here a few times and have been pretty satisfied with the choices and service.
No comment
Great venue. The various vendors have amazing food and the beer selection at Top Hops is great. With so many choices of food to choose from it's a hard decision.

This is a conveniently located food hall near Union Square. It has a good variety of cuisines including sushi, vegan comfort food, and healthy bowls. It's a great place to go with a group as there will be something for everyone. They have a seating area with tables as well as high top seating along the front window.

This is a really fun spot. There are 13 different restaurants so something for everyone. From pizza, pasta, sushi, coffee, sandwiches, tacos, falafel, playa bowls, salad bowls, vegan, and gluten free! So many options in this spacious food hall. I'd recommend going at a less busy hour so you can really enjoy the full experience. Great place to grab a few things with friends to share!!
No comment

Cool Place with lots of food choices and a bar, really clean space and looked like they had outdoor seating in the back. It was a bit to cold to sit outside but a nice option. Great service and friendly people from my experience visiting the first time.

Went here to check out the options.  They have alot of stalls but nothing special that you can't find in the area.  We settled on Bob White and got the chicken sandwich and fries.  Tbh the fries were very tasty as for the sandwich it was nothing special. The space itself has potential, I think rhey should've rented to vendors that aren't readily available in the area.  It will be a challenge at first but maybe a Hawaiian, Caribbean, or Philippine option would be a start.

I  expected to have a delicious cup of coffee by the look of the shop display. But my expectation wasn't fulfilled. The coffee tastes too light like the street vender's. I hope they will improve the taste and the quality.
Overpriced but good atmosphere. Would love for this to be my go-to lunch place, but it's too expensive. I was charged $2.18 for a regular Poland spring water bottle with no option for free tap water.

I love salt but I will note that everything was very salty especially the noodles and beans, I thought it was all very good regardless. We also tried the msg martini and the salted spritz both of those were really tasty. My biggest complaint would be the temperature in the restaurant, to be fair we went on one of the hottest days of the year, but it was almost unbearably hot inside.

Our server was not interested at all. Even when we tried to engage she was brusque and not friendly in the least. I rarely review but this spot is sadly overrated in my view. We won't be going back.

This was fantastic, every bit as good as we expected. First visit, we got the wonton soup, shrimp with walnuts, squid, rice noodles, cacio pepe, and mcrib. We loved every dish, with the biggest standout being the incredible rice noodles -- these were an absolute showstopper, and I'll be dreaming of them until next time we come. We both agreed the squid would also be an absolute must next time, and my wife had the wontons up there too. The shrimp and walnuts were excellent (so much better than it looks in pictures honestly), and we loved the cacio and mcrib as well, but there's so much else on the menu we want to try that we'd probably sub all those out next time. (Eg the trout, congee, chow mein, etc.)

The drinks were definitely soso imo. I thought the crispy squid could have been crispier but was pretty good. I was not a fan of the mcrib, I thought the cha siu could have been more tender. The xo noodles were pretty standard. I was a fan of the clams. We also got the poached chicken which was good but not amazing.

Great place, relaxed atmosphere despite the level of food they are putting out. Reasonably priced, again for the level of food you are getting. Loved it. Servers were super nice and seemed to be happy working there. Got to give them a plus for that.
Would love to give Bonnie's 5 stars soon especially since they have such a cute backstory! Unfortunately I both called and emailed recently and wish they were just a bit more responsive.

Justin is amazing!!! So attentive and fun. Let's get into the food. the crysyanthemum salad was a perfect palate cleanser and when we tasted the fresh oysters we immediately ordered 3 more. the orange wine bottle we ordered was the refreshing river that brought us to the immaculate dinner. THE MUSHROOM STICKY RICE!!!!!! We topped it off with the fish dish which put it over the top. This meal and experience was exquisite and we will come back for more.  --side note: as the birthday baby i receive the most delectable shot and utmost care from the well dressed and ever so classy bonnie sta

Exceptionalism on prime display--we thought we were special and wouldn't have to endure the overly salty dishes that many Yelpers have pointed out, but we were wrong. The cacio and pepe was absurdly salty!!! The jook (congee) was also a tad on the salty side. The oysters, chinese long beans, and honey walnut shrimp were all fantastic though. The drinks here are colorful and tasty -- we got the ribena highball and riptide and enjoyed them both. ALSO, just an FYI that the bathroom is basically a mini club-- the music is very loud in there, and the lights change colors. Overall, I would come back but I would not feel like I was missing anything if I never do

Love at 1st sip and 1st bite! Bonnie's is a Cantonese American restaurant in Brooklyn that serves nostalgic Hong Kong classic comfort dishes I ate growing up but with an American flare. The restaurant is very reminiscent of a 茶餐厅(Cha Chan Teng, a Hong Kong-style diner) with a very hipster Brooklyn interpretation. Also like a typical Hong Kong style diner, the restaurant was loud and lively.

Great meal at Bonnie's. Squid ($17) were crispy and light. I don't have a wok so this is a dish that I can't make at home. The lettuce bed was not soggy and the ranch dressing was on the runnier side but still good. 9/10. The Cha Siu McRib ($27) was much bigger than a regular McRib at McDonald's. It is a full sandwich. The hoisin sauce adds a smoky flavor and the thick cut pickles are fresh and really help counteract the sweetness and richness of the meat. Be warned that there is hot mustard on this sandwich and it's not evenly distributed so you may get a bite that's much spicier than the other bites. A wasabi-like level of spiciness. It isn't as fatty and juicy like a similarly priced Katz's deli sandwich. With this price, maybe value isn't its strong point, but it's pretty well executed. 8/10. The sundae ($12) was a nice way to end the meal. It's very unique, as the fried malted milk pieces were something I'd not had before. Buttered peanuts added more texture, which was good here. Normally I am hesitant to add nuts to sundaes, for fear that they will hurt the roof of my mouth, but these didn't. They were finely chopped. Ovaltine hot fudge was pretty sparse. I prefer regular hot fudge. 8/10. Service was prompt and friendly. Surprisingly busy on a Tuesday night. Maybe folks are going out to eat more these days, ahead of the transmissible BA5 wave which could elicit new lockdowns.
Very mediocre... would never come back. Overly salty and otherwise flavorless. No idea why this place is so popular.

This is a review I hate to write.  We went because of the NYT review.  While the food was quite good for its type, they do not have their act together yet for Celiac diners who are especially sensitive to gluten cross contamination.  We thought because they listed GF items on the menu it would be safe for Celiac patrons.  Despite being crystal clear about our needs for our Celiac diner, the first dish to arrive was a bean dish with gluten on top.  After getting that straightened out, it became clear that at least the serving staff & maybe the kitchen didn't understand that soy itself does not have gluten but soy sauce does.  The meal didn't sit well with our Celiac diner, so for the time being I would add this to the long list of Chinese restaurants to be avoided if you have Celiac.
The food wasn't good enough for the bad service. I said Happy New Year, no acknowledgment. Overpriced home-cooked style.

If full transparency I am related to Chef Owner Calvin Ng 9n my Mother's side if the family.  The food is traditional Cantonese dishes you would find at a home cooked meal or a dinner out in a old school Cantonese Restaurant in NYC Chinatown. The dishes Bonnie's serves I've ate many times at home cooked by my Grandfather and Mother or at a dinner in Chinatown. Chef Calvin takes these dishes and puts his take on them. The Dao Gok and Cacio E Pepe are both made with a traditional condiment Fuyu which is fermented bean curd. It has a very strong pungent taste but both dishes you only taste a hint of it and melds perfectly. Both dishes was outstanding and the Dao Gok was slightly different from the traditional dish. My favorite dish was the Black bean class with the steam eggs. It's actually two dishes combined. Normally both dishes would be separate entrees. The steam eggs was a perfect custard texture. Everything I ate was delicious but make sure to leave room for the Sundae which was phenomenal. It was awesome meal and hospitality was great. The GM Brad is a great guy. It was touching to see photos of my family adoring a wall. I will be back.

A friend of mine got reservations right when they open and you still have to wait outside (in the cold) with people who don't have reservations. You would think they could come up with a slightly better situation. It took us quite a while to be seated. The food is a little overpriced for what you are getting. Most of the food was a bit over salted. The staff is very pleasant but they are in no rush to get people in and seated. The cocktails were all $15 and apparently pre mixed per our server so we couldn't alter them. I got a Tsingtao which is just a cheap Budweiser style Chinese beer and that was $7. Overall this place is too expensive for what they offer. Most people are in there to take photos of the food and post it on social media.
No comment

Came here on a Sunday night around 7:00. Only had to wait about 30 mins for bar seating which was quicker then expected! We ordered the Mcrib, Chow Mein, and the Chow Nai Sundae. The Mcrib was definitely the highlight. The ribs were tender and the glaze was delicious, sweet and savory. The Chow Mein was also tasty, and I enjoyed the slight spice. The sundae was also yummy, but lacked a bit of ice cream. It felt like mostly whipped cream and fried milk, so definitely would have liked a bit more actually ice cream. But would definitely come back again!

Overall good meal but they didn't tell us in advance that we'd be seated outside (it didn't specify on Resy) and the outdoor seating is simply plastic tables and chairs with heat lamps... the lackluster atmosphere definitely takes away from the experience. Highlights were the shrimp dish and long beans, skip the McRib.

Amazing food! The wun tun brodo is phenomenal and I will definitely go back for more. The naw mai fan is a dish created by a genius. It left me with the impression of eating fried rice with cha siu (roasted meat). The xo cheung fun is fluffy and crispy with a lot of goodness. Service is great! Can't wait to get back !

Food is fairly good but it's way overpriced. Decor is not great as others have mentioned. Some of the dishes are fairly standard Cantonese fare (e.g. the shrimp with walnuts) and others are indeed more creative/modern (the cacio and pepe turned out way better than I would have guessed).

Great experience at Bonnie's. Food was delicious inventive and prepared perfectly. My favorite was the squid, perfectly crispy and super flavorful seasoning. Loved the chicken broth and the mushrooms and sticky rice too. The cacio e pepe was kind of a fun take but leaned more heavily towards being a faithful rendition of the dish. It was really good albeit maybe jived together less with the rest of the meal. The char siu McRib was tasty and prepared well I enjoyed it but I wouldn't go back for it, didn't really do much for me or add anything interesting. I would rather just get an actual char siu bun. The only dish I really didn't super enjoy was the stuffed whole trout. The flavors were nice but the meatloafy consistency wasn't for me. I got the black penicillin cocktail which was excellent. Service was great. My only real gripe is that their outdoor set up is not really suitable for cold weather. They have some blankets but it's not enclosed enough and the heaters just aren't strong enough for a cold night. Don't think they should offer the outdoor dining in the winter if they don't have the setup to make it comfortable enough. Loved the meal but sitting out on the cold definitely detracted a bit. Overall great experience, would recommend.

Every dish was spectacular and super creative. I've had Chinese green beans a million times but they felt special and so elevated for some reason at Bonnie's. Noodles were literally the perfect texture and chewiness. I like that they are thick  Also, prices aren't bad!

Take it for what it is and not what you want it to be, and you will certainly enjoy it here. Been twice and have enjoyed the food + service immensely both times! The Long Beans and XO noodles my fave both times. And the Fried milk pudding and Ovaltine ice cream is amazing. Extra points for their playlists
really overrated and overly sauced food, the portions are small and the prices are 30% higher now they've gotten in the mich guide.

Absurdity is a perfect word to describe Bonnie's. I am appalled at the prices of the dishes for a poor take at Cantonese food. There is NOTHING that is traditional or authentic about this Cantonese food. If you want culture and authenticity, Bonnie's is not that. The food and prices are fitting for the Williamsburg demographic: a group that has zero knowledge on Cantonese food. None of the staff members are Cantonese let alone Asian. If you want gentrified food that costs more than an arm feel free to go to Bonnie's. Objectively speaking, the taste of the food isn't bad, but the price for what it is is atrocious. These prices really makes the person believe in inflation that's for sure. Got damn walnut shrimp had oranges in it smfh. Better off going to Chinatown, flushing, dyker, 86 st Brooklyn and etc for more authentic food. If you wish to support TRUE culture, this is NOT it. My mom would've got a heart attack seeing what Bonnie's has done to our cultures food.

Can't believe how much hype... it's terrible. Overcooked, seasoned and small portions. We would never go again and question if we should speak to management. Everyone left feeling off too. Food is not good and the only saving grace is service is fast.

For a great number of us, it will be like revisiting disneyworld. The rides are all more sophisticated now but so are we. And we really like that.

This place is overhyped and completely overrated. We had the crispy fried squid (way too salty), the Chow Mein (peppers and meat didn't taste like much), and the Cheung Fun (extremely greasy). It really all tasted the same, and just like strong MSG and nothing more. No complex flavors, sophistication, or quality ingredients. Most places in Chinatown deliver this mediocre quality for half the price. We have no idea why this spot is so in demand. It cannot be for the food that's evident, but must be for hype and a certain coolness factor. We will stay away from it!

It's ok. Overpriced for sure and sooooo much hype it is hard to live up to. Had similar dishes recently in Elmhurst that run circles around the offerings here. Team works hard, kitchen cares, everyone is on their shit. Not their fault the likes of Eater and Infatuation and even the Times these days review the vibes and cool factor of a place and not the actual food. Again, it is fine food, but money is tighter and tighter these days - quality and quantity are not worth it.

I was really excited to try this restaurant. It's so hard to get a reservation but I'm really not sure why. The only thing that was good was the drinks. The food was very greasy, salty and just wasn't good. We don't finish our entrees. I definitely won't be coming back here.

The delivery menu is very limited, but that is the least of Bonnie's problems. We ordered the chicken nuggets which looked and tasted old. The breading was slightly rancid and the dipping sauce tasted store bought. We ordered the rib sandwich, the bun was soggy and in general everything was very unappetizing. And those two items were over  fifty dollars and took over an hour to delivery three blocks away.

Good but overhyped. Maybe I'm biased because I just spent a week eating in extraordinary, inexpensive Queens restaurants with my family. I'm not sure if the Infatuation is rating restaurants solely on vibes. Food was ok. I ordered the oysters, salt and pepper squid, long beans, cacio e pepe, Cheung fun, and ice cream.

Ugh, I wanted to like this place so much but it was underwhelming. I tried booking a rez here for months and was disappointed when I finally ate here. The best bites were the long beans and rice rolls and everything else was above average at best. This place is a lot of hype. Good meal, but not for the price.
The food and staff are so amazing that they are worth a yelp review! One of my top restaurants. Can't go wrong with anything on the menu!

Wowwww! Amazing from the gin msg martini, clams, mc rib, to the service. Everything was out of this world. Walked in at 5:30 on a Saturday, waited 30 mins before they seated us at a table and gave us the most delicious shooters on the house. Will be returning to try more menu items

Food remain excellent and staff member treated you more than a customer. Will definitely come back for more foods.

I ordered the Taiwanese beef noodle soup ($12.50 w/o tax) and the pan fried pork & chive dumplings ($7 w/o tax).  I recommend the beef noodle soup as it came with enough meat and noodles.  The soup itself was more tomato forward then expected, but it was good.  The pan fried pork & chive dumplings were decent, but a bit too burnt for my taste.  The restaurant was very light and bright.  Tables were available for customers to sit and eat in as a fast casual restaurant.

Small spot robust flavors! My second time here in five days. Came alone on 1/8 then again with the bf  on 1/14. We were welcomed, they remembered me, that was very special. On 1/14 Saturday late dinner (9:30pm reservation), we ordered the prix fixe from the bar, everything on the menu. We were not disappointed. Starter was salad w miso dressing and an injera type roti bread; it was light and delicious. Then we had a fresh baked sour dough with fresh soft in house made sea salt butter (Amazing). For dinner we had the tile fish and beef shoulder, both delectable and full of flavor. Tried the wizard's comb cocktail and loved it. At dessert we shared the passion biscuit and chocolate situation. Both were wonderful. So for $65 prix fixe it's a deal. High quality, bright flavors and 5star service! (We ended with hot espressos, also great)

Nice ambiance and service. The food was good but not enough to justify $165 price tag. We dine out every weekend and try to sample restaurants on "best" lists, so have a good reference point. If  you do pre-fix with no choice of substitute for this price, it has to be special. It was not. Scallop dish was good but I had a few gritty pieces. Meat had nice sauce and flavor, but a bit tough. We went to Nura last week and the dishes were more imaginative and tastier for more then 30 % less. I would give it solid 3.5 stars, because it doesn't meet expectations of what it should be.

Visited a friend in NY who raved about this restaurant and said we had to go while I was here to experience their 9 course meal. Ohhh and what an experience it wasThe ENTIRE staff is welcoming from the moment you enter the restaurant. Our server was amazing in helping me to choose my wine selections for the evening and the restaurant was able to accommodate my dietary restrictions within the menu for the evening. I preferred one dessert more but neither were my favorites however that didn't take away from my overall experience. Each course built upon the next. Everything was exquisite. If you're in NY specifically Brooklyn and want a one of a kind dining experience, I highly recommend Oxalis.

One of dish is tasted like fried Chinese turnip cake but with a twist of truffle that tickles your taste buds. Every course is definitely a surprise. Sophisticated menu, service and venue worth Michelin's appreciation. Check for the fixed price menu in the veranda which offers nice fusion cuisine delicacies..

Went to get fine dining from this Michelin-Star-owned restaurant. We got the Carte Blanche platter, which was $70 each. The food was admittedly very delicious, many of the bites were amazing and the flavors burst in your mouth. The tuna with squid ink was good. However, I have one huge gripe with this restaurant, and it was that we were here from way too long, from evening to nighttime. This is because the dishes came out super slowly despite finishing our portions very fast. The ambiance of the restaurant was excellent though.

Oh boy this place is delicious!!! I'm so happy that I made the time to come here and try a lot of great food. Went to the back garden where they do their a la carte menu as opposed to the prix fixe within the main restaurant where you can see the kitchen. The service was impeccable as everyone was greeting me and all the staff was super friendly. We ended up eating with a chef of the restaurant as someone in our party knew her, so that was cool to get a glimpse into Oxalis' style and learn more about what we were eating. We ended up ordered... everything on the menu! My highlights were certainly the sourdough bread (which it seems like everyone and their mother is talking about); that butter was special!! But more than that, I loved the tomato spread with the rosemary lavender bread; I could have eaten that all up! I think the mushroom kebab (which just isn't a kebab at all) fell a bit flat, but still - all in all, this was a SPECIAL meal. The buttermilk dessert + the peach tart really rounded it all out. And my orange wine cocktail was delicious and served in the perfect glass. I know they have a more rotating menu here, so I'd love to come back sooner rather than later to try some great food. It came out to a bit less than $100/person, so considering it is a 1 Michelin-star place and we got everything on the menu, I think that's great; each dish isn't quite expensive so you can come in for a drink and some food and not break the budget. Enjoy!

They're really good right now and they're only going to get better, unless success and ambition makes them think there is something bigger and better than Prospect Heights waiting for them.
Delicious and able to accommodate vegetarian diets for the course meal. Always great to see Oxalis's take on the season's ingredients

column3: South Kansas City, Kansas City, MO
column6: Had an outstanding meal at Oxalis. We opted for the carte blanche menu, which offered 9+ courses thoughtfully created by the chef.  Husband has the non alcoholic beverage pairing which he thoroughly enjoyed. I had the pineapple cocktail which was one of the tastiest cocktails I've had in awhile. Every course was delicious but we especially enjoyed the potato and seafood stew. I'm not sure how to describe it but to say it was savory and delicate and so rich in flavor. We also loved the flounder dish which was so fresh and both the cherry blossoms and green strawberry added so much to the dish. Staff was friendly and informative. Don't miss out on this excellent restaurant.

There are some hits and misses with the carte blanche. Their sourdough was truly phonomenal - crispy on the outside, warm and soft on the inside (it's SO GOOD). Some of the food was simply way too salty for my liking. Flavors at oxalis tend to be bold, and sometimes not matching. One star off for the taste of some of the dishes. But their service is amazing! Their mocktail pairing was also super nice!

I visited Oxalis on a night when they had an event with Suntory Whiskey so there were some extra items on the menu. The food was delicious and drinks were amazing. My husband and I both had drinks from the special menu, and also tried the special dessert the cherry blossom roll. The rest was from their regular menu and we loved all of it, but the lamb collar was slightly underwhelming especially considering it's the most expensive item on the menu. Not as tender as one would expect for meet that has been cooked for 16h. I still give it a 5 star because, overall it was a 5 star experience!

The menu here was surprisingly complex and insanely flavorful! I'd booked dinner here on a lark, not knowing what to expect, and was so glad I'd found Oxalis. Upgrade for the truffle supplement, you will not regret it!

Oxalis features a la carte and tasting menu seatings, and we opted for the latter.  The experience was truly unique as dishes were composed of ingredients, sauces and technique I don't often see together.  One standout was the pumpkin tempura (perfectly fried) with miso sauce (which had a nice spicy kick!).  I also loved the hake with a lovely herbal sauce.  The restaurant is particularly proud of their sour dough starter and feature it in a handful of dishes too.  The bread with butter was phenomenal.  Fermented sauces and ingredients are also used throughout which ties the meal together in a thoughtful way.  The vibe at the restaurant is comfortable and welcoming.

Absolutely outstanding. I have been to Oxalis no fewer than three times for their tasting menu and they do not disappoint. Yes yes the sourdough is, in fact, out of this world but so are the thoughtful, ingredient-driven preparations of the other dishes. The technique and talent of the staff shines in each bright and flavorful bite. Oxalis is far and away my favorite restaurant in New York City right now, its inventive but plainly delicious food bolstered by an amazingly friendly and welcoming staff (a rarity in this city).

Mom took me and the fiancé here to welcome her new son-in-law to the family. This place didn't disappoint at all. The outside of the shop wasn't very impressive but once you walk in, it definitely felt very warm and inviting. My mom unfortunately made a mix up and didn't notice she put herself on the waitlist instead of getting the confirmed reservation. The staff did their best and offered their a la carte menu to us along with some free champagne (Obi Wine Keno Blue - cute play on Star Wars). Luckily as we were considering whether we should stay or not (not saying their a la carte wasn't appealing but mom wanted the big welcome for the new son-in-law), the general manager, Adrienne. stepped in and informed us someone cancelled. We were very lucky. (They usually have a set amount of ingredients and courses set for reservations so if you don't have reservations, from what I was told, they don't squeeze people in.) Everything was exceptional from presentation to taste. Service was wonderful and if I could come back more often for date night I would. Later, we found out their head chef (and owner) were originally from the West Coast (West Coast is the best coast - makes perfect sense why the food was so bomb) and moved out to New York to start his business here. Compliments to the chef and thank you to the wait staff for the wonderful service they provided.

Highly recommended for an adult evening out, special date night, or an occasion to celebrate. You'll enjoy an excellent meal, carefully crafted and conceptualized, from start to finish. I'd also suggest, if you're a duo, that you request the table with front row seats of the kitchen and the chef at work. I thoroughly enjoyed the added bonus of a show and it was really neat to see the composition and plating of each dish making its way to us. Oxalis offers a prix fixe dinner service (offerings change nightly) with optional wine pairing at an additional cost. My spouse and I elected to go all in and we loved the complete experience of everything being expertly selected for us - what a fun and delicious treat! We also relished in being surprised with the menu offerings for the evening when we sat at our places (hidden but neatly placed under our napkin and bread plate). Don't be afraid to ask questions - the staff, even the chef, are very friendly and knowledgeable about the dishes, the creative ingredients as well as the wine pairings. I was also shocked by my favorite course of the evening; glancing at the menu I knew I was looking forward to the soft shell crab and while everything was excellent, I was absolutely blown away by the potato, ramp, and kombu spring stew. It was so unexpected for me, I loved every bite. Both flavor and texture variety were perfect. That said, be open to being pleasantly surprised. Oxalis will come through in an amazing way and provide a very memorable dining experience. The hubby and I will absolutely return, we're already set to try the separate bar menu in the back of the establishment.

If I could give this amazing restaurant 10 stars, I would. Chef Nico and his staff are top notch. We had a party of 4, expecting great things and they exceeded expectations in a very big way! The meal was truly the best I've ever had. Each of the 11 dishes were works of art, with flavors that were out of this world. The Kampachi, the first course was so savory, like nothing I've ever tasted. Literally, each bite, I closed my eyes to experience the incredible blend of flavors. We had two more appetizers that were equally fantastic. We also did the wine pairing which had perfect choices for all the courses. I added caviar to the fluke, which was outstanding. The beef with walnut miso, and black garlic melted in my mouth with the greatest flavors. Three different desserts put this evening over the top. Chef Nico and the phenomenal staff made us feel so welcome. Chef Nico, you truly love what you do and it shows in your creative food ideas, presentations and phenomenal food. This Michelin star restaurant is a real gem. Bravo, Nico and we will return! Thank you all!

We opted for the $60 six-course carte blanche menu and were blown away by the delicious and unique flavor combinations. We felt like we were getting all of the service and quality of a Michelin star restaurant without any of the stuffiness or pretension. This is an incredible addition to the neighborhood, and I know we will be coming back soon. Make your reservation now before it becomes impossible to get one.

In the 5 years I've lived in New York, probably the best meal I've had. If you like surprises, not having to choose anything about the meal is fun, and the wine pairing was the perfect complement to each dish.
This is the best fine dining in the neighborhood. Bright, airy, not too expensive. It's just so great; fresh and seasonal food, creative plating. I'm so glad it's there for special occasions.
No comment
No comment

I would like to review the food at this restaurant but I have been unable thus far to actually eat there. Reservations are as of now not hard to get, but they've canceled me twice. They promised to accommodate me in the future, but it's getting frustrating. I will amend this review to include the food if I ever get to eat it.

I dined at Oxalis shortly after the NY Times review. My Gf was finishing up a sales meeting nearby and she suggested that we try Oxalis. We rarely make reservation's, but we arrived early enough to be seated. The space is very attractive, and it has a very nice vibe. The nabe is full of ues transplants, and on this particular evening it appeared that every one of them had invited their parents to dinner. I thought that I was in La Goulue for a minute. The food is good not great. The wines by the glass were terrible, but the staff were all polite, and very gracious. I guess that they need some time to age and I hope to try Oxalis again in the future.

A superb restaurant with wonderful service and a unique menu featuring inspired use of unusual herbs. It's the perfect place for a romantic dinner for two or a night of fine dining and drinking with old friends. Memorable things: the beautiful greenhouse-like dining area in the back of the restaurant, the herb-infused cocktails, the extraordinarily delicious food, the fact that we could get a table immediately, the prompt and friendly service. Frankly, I'm surprised this place isn't completely overrun by reservations weeks in advance; the food is on par with that of the ever-booked Olmsted around the corner, and in several ways more interesting.

We went for New Years and had an incredible experience. The food was amazing - especially the beef tartar and the poached oysters and the dessert - and the service was superb. The space was beautiful. A world class restaurant in Brooklyn!

First date night away from the baby for the husband's birthday and it was everything. We were treated like royalty just because I let them know we were celebrating- the service was tremendous and one of the owners is right there alongside the staff talking to all the guests. We reserved the dining area where it's tasting menu only- every course was so unique and delicious. As an added bonus, they throw in a couple things not listed. We can't wait to get back and check out the bar room which looked beautiful. Great addition to the neighborhood food scene!

Holiday spirit indeed.  I got food poisoning over thanksgiving and had to cancel my reservation, did so in advance but was told there was a $60 fee.  I explained the situation and this was not a last minute cancellation but no budging.  Would have been nice to get a heads up when I canceled.  Was really looking forward to dining here but a restaurant with no budging/heart is not one I want to support.
No comment

My mother and I stumbled into this gem after visiting the Brooklyn Museum. The prix fixe menu is a bargain for $70. This restaurant would be at home in Manhattan for twice the price. The staff were wonderful and the service was among the best I've experienced in a long time. Every course was a small masterpiece. We loved it and would go back!

Such a great place. Whether you come for the amazing tasting menu which is truly delicious  or to just sit outside and enjoy a cocktail in the garden, Chef Nico, Steve and the amazing staff make this  an unbelievable experience! This place just flows from the moment you are seated to saying goodbye, everything just works beautifully!

Absolutely best dining experience I have had in a long time. Every dish was amazing and my friends and I could not stop talking about it afterwards. For this price point, you have to go. I will definitely be back and bring many people with me. We talked to the chef afterwards and he was so kind and really cannot wait to see the growth of this fabulous restaurant.

Excellent, excellent restaurant. From the attentive and warm staff to the extremely delicious dishes.  We had the tasting menu and for desert we were surprised with candles for our anniversary.  Really loved the delicacy and unique flavors of all the different dishes. It's really rare to find an affordable tasting menu, especially in Brooklyn. I really hope this pop up becomes permanent!

So sorry not to be able to be positive- we were so looking forward to this place. We've been living in Brooklyn for 12 years now. We love good food. One of us grew up in Paris and we love to spend a good buck on dinner - when it's worth it. We got a tiny sized "flatbread " (bad pizza) for $17. The other dishes were fine but still not worth it. Made us feel like gentrification makes us all chumps - a little cabbage with a drizzle of vinegar can be $14 because hey, rent is high. Sadly would not return here again. (On a side note- very nice decor; Service was perfectly good; the wine was fine if overpriced.) Did not stay for dessert.
No comment

Definitely worth a second visit. Their menu prix fixe menu is very high end and worth the $60. They pay great attention to detail and the meal tantalizes your taste buds.The staff is very nice and accommodating. Awesome!!

This place is already packed but it's bound to completely blow up soon. The service, the food, the drinks, the presentation - and the reasonable price for all of these things - everything blew us away. It's truly a gem in the neighborhood. We sat in the bar room and ordered one of each dish, which was perfectly shareable between the 4 of us. The farro and beef in particular were our favorites and the citrus cocktail was so delicious. We will definitely be coming back to try more drinks and the tasting menu.
Really great food with delicious balanced flavours. The waiting staff were really attentive. Highly recommended.

So excited to have another food destination on the Crown/Prospect Heights border! As soon as we stepped inside, we started to understand why Eater had named Oxalis one of the top restaurants in Brooklyn 2019. Gabriel and his staff were charmingly polite and warm. We ordered a la carte: started with flatbread with duck offal (deliciously rich and appropriate for a wintry night) and chicory salad with carmelized anchovy (creamily addictive dressing, even if we were expecting pieces of anchovies); then enjoyed the cabbage with egg yolk (wish I could get the recipe) and grilled beef with horseradish (tender, fresh and filling).   The coffee chocolate cream cheese was heavenly. One of the best meals we've had in a long time. One of Brooklyn's finest in innovative cooking without any fussiness or pretentiousness.

Remarkable experience! Staff amazing.Food incredible! So much fun. HIGHLY recommend! Ok, so Yelp wants me to make my already highly complimentary review longer to actually post it. So I will because, while i hate to type on my phone, I like this restaurant so much. I hope this works.

What a phenomenal experience. I went with my wife for our 1 year anniversary, and the staff treated us like celebrities. The beverage pairing is a must, and the cocktails at the bar were extremely unique and delicious. The food was absolutely excellent, our favorite was the beef shoulder that was cooked for 16 hours and coated with a crunchy herb rub. Highly recommend!

If there was an extra star on yelp, I'd give it. First persons to great us, the Chefs! The food was so good I was texting my (industry sommelier friends) all night long. It's that good. I could have went face first into that mushroom pot-au-feu. Get there before the reviews as it surly will blow up. They don't have a liquor license yet, but send you a recc from their favorite bar. Reserve and go! $60 bucks for a 5 course tasting, in Manhattan $300 easy.
No comment
The Thanksgiving fixed menu was a bit pricey but worth it, the service was excellent and friendly.

Way overpriced for a fine brunch. With so many delicious, well-priced brunch options in the 'hood, we were disappointing here (though staff was all lovely). From past reviews, sounds like dinner is the way to go at Oxalis.

The food was exceptional, the service was impeccable and I highly recommend going for the pre-fixe dinner.  We had both non-alcoholic and normal drink pairing and both were unique and delicious. The duck breast was probably the best I've had.

GO! As simple as that. But in the interest of elaborating: probably the most creative, imaginative and unique combinations of food and tastes; wonderful, smiley staff, great cocktails, and totally reasonable. I think this place should be on most people's lists, and hope it is around for a long time.

Service is super attentive, the food is great, (first course needs a little work, the carrots aren't functional with the toothpick), the n/a beverage tasting is insane. Every one that they give, they gave 4 drinks, went absolutely perfectly with the dish. Kinda wished the sesame cookie was given before dessert because it's really strong and lingers for a long time in your mouth. But seriously, don't sleep on this place. It's going to do great things.

Oxalis was a superb experience from the moment I walked in. Friendly staff (from the open kitchen chefs to host and bartender), pleasant & relaxing ambiance, and delicious food throughout the whole tasting menu. Highly recommend this spot for those that are open to unexpected tasting menus and unique beverage pairings, all for a reasonable price. I definitely plan on bringing more friends here, you don't want to miss this experience!

Best dinner date/restaurant for a special occasion in Brooklyn by a landslide. When we have friends visiting and we are trying to show them the best spots in town, Oxalis ranks at the very top. If you're not a big drinker, they have an *excellent* non-alcoholic drink pairing with the tasting menu. Makes dinner much more accessible when you're with a group of drinkers and non-drinkers. Couldn't recommend Oxalis highly enough.
No comment

Creative menu with lots of unexpected flavors. The tasting menu is a gastronomic feast topped only by the quirky and delicious wines. Excellent staff who really love what they do and enhance the experience with their knowledge and story telling. Truly a gem of a restaurant.

Great vibe and great service. I went here post proposal and my soon to be wife loved it!  HIGHLY RECOMMEND 'NON-ALCOHOLIC' pairing with the meal! In-house sodas were actually better than wine pairing... sounds crazy but one must try to understand what i am saying! So worth it

Behind the frosted glass facade at 791 Washington Ave is Oxalis, where wonderful things are being made and served. This restaurant works perfectly for the part of Brooklyn it's in, which you kind of feel before you even open the door. The quality of the dishes the Oxalis team serve will astound you and are worth every dollar. They do rotating tasting menus, but also offer food and drink off an ala carte menu in the back half of the restaurant. You can tell that Nico and Co. know what they are doing, and also, most importantly, that they care. Being able to watch the chefs and cooks working so diligently in the open kitchen is quite humbling, but also inspiring. I think we could all learn a thing or two about delicious, fresh, new ways of approaching food and it'll be fun to see it happen here. Aspiring chefs, foodies, and regular people of all walks of life, in and out of Brooklyn, should give Oxalis a try. Maybe you'll learn something new, see something great, or just enjoy a nicely prepped and prepared meal, served to you by their nice staff. The last time I ate there, I tired the pig trotter and it was my favorite. I also had a dessert made with cream cheese ice cream, which brought out my inner fat kid, for sure. I'm going backwards now, but the brioche bread was amazeballs. I am really excited for Oxalis in 2019 and can't wait to see what is on the way!
Best restaurant in Brooklyn.  Not to be missed. Beautiful spot, delicious food, lovely and knowledgable staff.  Seriously, go.

I have been to some of the best restaurants in NYC (Eleven Madison Park, Per Se, Le Bernadin, Aska ...) but I was blown away by the inventiveness and quality of the food at Oxalis.  So delicious course after course it is hard to even pick the best.  The creamy farro with snails was unforgettably mouthwateringly creamy and verdant and unique.  The beef tongue was perfectly salty, crispy, crunchy and meaty all at the same time. And the goat cheese dessert was a wonderful end to a memorable meal that I will definitely want to repeat.

We just went to this place for a special anniversary, and we absolutely loved it. Upon making a reservation and noting my dietary restrictions, the manager wrote an email to confirm that they would be preparing a special menu. When we arrived, there was a beautiful table set with a personalized note wishing us a happy anniversary. They poured us delicious bubbles to celebrate (twice!), and the food was fabulous. It was an amazing meal and the warm and attentive service made us feel right at home. We're excited to go back with friends and family!

Oxalis' food, asthetic, and playlist are incredible!!! I've been here several times and most recently tried the set menu. There was a mushroom dish that was absolutely divine- the broth was incredible I could've had ten bowls of that alone. As of the last time I visited they didn't have s liquor license yet but their non-alcoholic drinks are all so amazing I didn't even care. My favorite drink was the sparking jasmine tea.

We came here on a friends rexommendatjon and w had a fantastic experience. Creative menu, friendly staff and an overall relaxing, but not too quiet, ambiance. The music was also top notch. At the end of the meal we couldn't decide which dish was our favorite and we each nominated two different ones as our personal favorites - which is always a good sign. We will definitely be coming back!

So delicious! We did the $60 tasting menu with the $15 non-alcoholic beverage pairing it was so unique and incredible. On top of amazing food there service was on point, so professional and enthusiastic!  Highly recommend!

I've been lucky enough to eat at many incredible restaurants in New York and while they're great, not many are standouts among the rest. Oxalis is without a doubt, the most pleasant, refreshing and jaw-droppingly delicious meal I've had in years. The food was otherworldly. We had the prix fixe and each dish was better than the last. The service was fantastic as was the atmosphere. I have a ton of food allergies to raw whole fruits and vegetables (I know, my life sucks) and they were so accommodating and created two entirely different dishes for me (though what my family ate for those courses was apparently also fantastic). To top it all off, the dessert (goat milk with honey and thyme - trust me, totally different than what you're probably imagining right now) was perhaps the best dessert I've had in my life and I've come to to the realization that was the peak of my dessert journey and I'm fine with that. Overall, a magical, warm, inviting, flavorful, surprising experience. Side note: try their Jasmine Tea Soda (WOW!).

Really good, but I know Americans aren't used to paying more for higher quality Indian food which comes at a premium. I got the bhaji pav ($13.99) which was really really good. The spice was on point and I could literally tell by eating it that the ingredients were just of a higher quality. Of course as one knows with places where the quality is good, the portion size of the dishes are smaller. But to be honest, I think it is good because usually portion sizes at restaurants are inflated. I will come back occasionally due to the price point.

We went the for Saturday dinner had Masala Dosa and masala chai. This was good food and liked the decor of the restaurant.

My dreams of having shiv sagar type restaurants in NY, have been answered. This place is AMAZING! we have tried pretty much all the dishes on the menu. My favorites however are the pani puri, bhel puri, bhakri pizza with amul cheese and bahubali sandwich. This will be a constant till I live in Manhattan.

I visited NYC yesterday and the person next to me was an Indian from an area close Delhi. and in talking about pav bhaji, she recommended Honest as a great place for that and vegetarians. Unfortunately, when I went I was rather full from a late lunch so just had some samosas, what struck me was how fresh they were, delicious. Honest serves vegetarian Indian street food and it feels and looks that way. I know a lot about Indian food but I am not an Indian, but it strikes me that the  food here would be a cure from homesickness by someone from India. Will definitely come back.
No comment

HIGHLY recommend coming to Honest for some delectable chaat!! Honestly, the food tasted like the street stalls in India. I tried the vada pav, kattappa sandwich, dahi puri, and pav bhaji - and oh my god, every bit was so so good. The staff is very friendly, and the food is very fresh and tastes amazing. I've tried chaat at quite a few places in NYC, and I don't think many places compare to Honest. The restaurant is cute, chic, and I love the instagrammable sign that they have inside. Great place to hangout with friends, for a quick bite, or a nice dinner. I will definitely be coming back again to try more!
No comment

Loved everything we ordered here - pau bhaji, and special pizza. They even made a small size sada dosa for my one year old and she relished it! Great quality with great taste. The place was very clean and neat. Loved the ambiance. Coming back for sure!

This place is a gem. Love that it's right in the middle of the west village and has affordable prices. If you are an NYU student you can get an additional discount ! The food was amazing and portions were huge. I recommend going family style and sharing a few dishes.

Small, unassuming place, order at front and they bring your food to your table.  It's definitely different than typical Indian food. They call it Street Food. The plates are small and meant to be shared. Everything seemed fresh, nothing frozen or reheated. Good quality ingredients. Started with bhaji pav, which is kind of a loose mashed potato curry served with buttery rolls for dipping. It was pretty tasty. We then had some samosas which I thought were just ok. Then we had paneer chili gravy which was grilled paneer cheese with veggies in a spicy sauce. That was my favorite dish. Also got something called a mango falooda which is kind of like a mango lassi but with nuts, mango ice cream, and thin noodles. Apparently it's a very popular  Indian street drink. My friend and I really didn't care for it. It actually wasn't bad, but those noodles were pretty off-putting for us. Maybe it's an acquired taste. Overall, an interesting meal, the restaurant was basic but very clean and bright and pretty, and the service was very good. But the food itself, while interesting, wasn't actually that great. I'm glad I tried it, but wouldn't rush to go back.

Perfect place for Indian chat around Greenwich area. Their menu options are great for street food nostalgia and the taste is original. As 'Desi' as it could get. I had the Samosa Chat and it was amazing .

This place caught my eye when I walked by it. Vibrant and colorful which I love. I decided to go in and was greeted very friendly. I asked what was good on the menu and was offered a few suggestions. I ended up picking the Bhaji Pav and the Hangover juice (lemon, ginger, carrot). You could sit anywhere which is pretty cool. The decor is spacious, bright, and inviting. I ended up sitting in the back to look at the backyard view which was nice. A kind woman brought my food to me and saw I was taking selfies which she asked if she can take the picture for me instead. The pictures she took were so lovely! I appreciate her lol The food and juice overall were delicious. It was a very calming environment to eat in. I definitely will come back and recommend it!
Highly recommend this vegetarian restaurant! Must try the pau bhaji with cheese and the dabang dosa!
No comment

most horrible customer service. Our order was wrongly served to another customer and we kept waiting forever for it to arrive. the server girl realized it.  But gave us no update and neither any apology for the delayed service!!! very rude and proud girls man the restaurant. I wonder if they will ever get a return customer. The whole time that we were waiting, we were hearing loud conversations amongst the girls in the kitchen about their personal life. No wonder the mistake! Owners please be aware of what is going on in your business.
Dropped in for a quick paani poori. Honestly I can make them much better and I don't know how to cook.
SO good. My favorite desi street food in the city, tastes like I'm eating roadside in Ahmedabad!

I have a nut allergy and they assured me their samosas were nut free after explaining my allergy to the person working there. Within minutes of eating the food, I had a severe allergic reaction and had to be hospitalised. First time in my life having to use an epi pen and spent hours in the ER. I will never eat here again!!!!

Great food. Loved the dabang dosa, pani puri. Also the person at counter was suuuuper nice and very kindly made the best recommendations. He was also thoughtful enough to space out my large order appropriately so I have the best experience. Can't wait for them to open more of the restaurants in the city.

'Honest Indian Restaurant' is a great addition to the Greenwich Village area. The interior is very spacious, clean, and aesthetic - with lots of murals and art decor. Everything on the menu is vegetarian. We tried a variety of dishes - Kattappa, Veg Hakka Noodle, Samosa Chaat, Pav Bhaji, and Pani Puri. The Bhaji Pav and Samosa Chaat was my favorite. Pav Bhaji is their signature dish, so I had to try it! It was a simple, homey dish. Every bite of the Samosa Chaat was loaded with flavor - sauce, chickpea, vegetables, and fruits (pomegranate and apples).

Doesn't look like much when you pass by but OMG is this place good. Reminds me of my moms home cooking! I'll be coming at least once a week!

The food was very tasty and place was modern, clean and spacious. We had the plain dosa, gobi manchurian, pav bhaji, dahi puri, falooda and chai. Everything was delicious. It has the same quality and taste as chaat that you would get in India.
Really good, quick service, and friendly staff! Friend had the mango lassi and said it was great too

This is basically an Indian fast food restaurant. Best for a quick lunch. The food is just okay. They say it's Indian street food, so it's not to be confused with what you would expect from a typical Indian restaurant.

I picked up the Dabang Dosa and the Vada Pav for dinner last night and it was incredible. The sambhar for the dosa was so so good, didn't care much for the coconut chutney. The food was so good that I ordered the Pav Bhaji and the Kattappa Sandwich for lunch today, and once again, they were both so delicious. The texture and the taste of the pav bhaji gravy was perfect. The Kattappa sandwich could have been more spicy but it was really really good. I'm going to try literally everything on their menu. I'm Indian and I definitely recommend this place.
Delicious.  I had the chili paneer (dry) and the kaju anjeer milkshake, and they were extremely tasty.  I'm so excited to have a good chaat + Indo-Chinese place in the West Village!

Ate here for lunch. The Bhaji Pav is incredible and perfectly spiced. Surprisingly large inside; I was able to set up my laptop on my table while I ate. Great background music. I expect to come here a lot!
Had a wonderful experience at Honest. Tied thali, puri, pao bhaji, dosa, kulfi. Great food, great service.
I visited this location twice while I was on vacation in NYC. Food was amazingggg. Location was clean and service was nice. I wish we had Honest here in Arizona lol.  Must try, if you are in NYC.
I loved every single bite oft paneer roll! Really good flavoring, super fresh and tasty.

So glad I stopped in to try this new place in our neighborhood! We had the Bhaji Pav, the Manchurian dumplings, and the samosas. Everything was delicious and there's lots on their menu I'd like to try next time. You can ask for different spice levels if you'd like, and pretty much anything can be made vegan- and there are so many interesting vegetarian options! Your food is made fresh when you order. It was great.
Classic honest. Pav bhaji cannot disappoint. Glad we have this one in NYC now. One of the best places for Indian food in the city.

Cozy place . Great friendly service. You must order the empanadas they were delicious. My husband had the lemon chicken with vegetables which he enjoyed. My son had the salmon with the yummy mashed yuca and kale. I had the gnocchi bolognese so flavorful. Can't wait to return.

Stopped by for takeout and got the parrillada for two. The steaks were cooked well and not dry and the sausage was excellent. I wish they gave more rice and beans with this meal as that seemed to be enough for one.

What a great spot to visit! We made it just in time to grab a couple of drinks while on happy hour special. Happy hour ends at 7. The gentlemen who waited on us was super sweet. He was attentive to our table and even repeated the specials twice (hearing through the masks is tough) Margaritas were great. However, the sangria was a bit.... different. Not horrible but definitely not something I wanted to order again. Now if you've been to other Brazilian spots you know the meats tend to be a bit on the saltier side. However, the flavor is like no other. Meat was cooked perfectly and the yucca purée was delicious. The rice and beans also tasted great nothing out of the ordinary. The star of this meal however was the BRAZILIAN FLAN! Perfect way to finish the meal off.

The restaurant has a wonderful ambiance the drinks and our appetizers were great. When it came to our meals the steak wasn't seasoned at all. The Salmon dish was great! Our sides also lacked seasoning. I guess we had higher expectations for an Argentinian restaurant we've been to other similar places and the food is seasoned amazing. The Flan was delicious. If I was to go again I would do drinks and apps.

I've been to El Mate twice now and I will be back again! I'm Uruguayan and love a good asado. The steak was delicious and the ensalada rusa was also great. The only thing I didn't like was that the server asked the person I was dining with "Oh you finished everything! You liked it, huh?" after they ate everything on their plate. ¡¡Super fuera de lugar, eso no se pregunta!! However, the food was very good.

Overall a really good experience, go support local small businesses and restaurants! We sat at the outdoor patio which shielded us from the light rain. Flavorful and strong. The food was filling and tasteful. But the chicken empanadas were they highlight of the night, and the meats had a great flavor and cooked as asked. Would definitely come back.

This was such a nice restaurant. The staff are very friendly and helpful with explaining the menus. Food, is amazing. I always start with the empanadas. It's food porn. Brazil Brooklyn-style. Lovely cocktails. Good servers ! Music Sunday night. Chicken wings, salads and fine Brazilian stews. Small street side room and a large covered back yard.  Fun place. Staff nice.
Love this restaurant. The staff are top notch. Always ask for a recommendation, you will not be disappointed.

Thank you guys for a great night out.  They were able to accommodate my party of 14 and we had plenty of room in the back of the diningroom. Also had a great looking backyard as well.  Drink orders were taken shortly after we sat down.  Waitress was very patient with everyone deciding what they wanted and the recommendations of shared empanada appetizers were great.  The crust was light and flaky and all the different fillings we got were moist and flavorful.  Large amounts of meat and steak for all the entrees, especially the mixed grill (must have).  Constant came by to refill drinks and clear the table.  We didn't stay for dessert but they sent over 3 plates of flan for the table to share and everyone agreed it was awesome.  The perfect balance of creamy and dense and the caramel was spot on.  Rave reviews from the whole party.  Looking forward to going back.

Yucca mashed, entraña , chimichurri, empanadas , so dam good. Our new favorite for steak and delicious Malbec wine.

I recently celebrated my birthday with close friends at  El Mate, my first dinner outing in months (all while following CDC Covid-19 guidelines), the staff definitely took the steps necessary to secure our safety and theirs. My friends and I were accommodated in their patio, which was such a great treat. The patio is beautiful and spacious, it's easy to forget that you're in Brooklyn. The food, service and atmosphere were stellar. I can't recommend it enough. I'm looking forward to my next visit and so are my friends. Thanks Luis and rest of staff, you guys made us feel very comfortable and allowed us to have a great time.

You have to put the Chimi sauce on everything! Just like the BF did. We ordered the Parillada for 2. This comes with Short Ribs, Chorizo, Blood Sausage, Argentine Sausage, Mollejas, Chicken and Skirt Steak.  Our sides were the mashed yucca, rice and black beans and I got a side of fries. The fries are fresh cut fries, NOT the stuff from a bag. This is a plus since my mom makes fries like this. The mashed yucca tastes better than mash potatoes and the rice and beans were good. The meats are cooked according to your request so they were delicious! We finished a jar of chimichurri sauce and the waitress bought us another one. Yes, its THAT GOOD!!! I opted for dessert and the waitress suggested the caramel empanada with ice cream. Which was so good i finished it. Oh and we also ended up ordering a full pitcher of red sangria. I came to this place with recommendation of my sister and brother-jn law. We were a party of 4 Adults and 1 toddler and 1 baby, and as we were sat we were immediately ask and accommodated for high chairs for the kids. Service here is warm, friendly and timed perfectly on point. We were greeted by Luis our server that was ready to take our beverage order right away and provides us with water. The menu consist of some Latin Apps and salads but 90% of the rest is pure Argentinian dishes fish, pasta, meats and sides. We first ordered the breaded chicken and fries for the kids, the order came out right on time and they even sliced the chicken in the right bite size for the baby and toddler, then ordered the Argentinian Empanadas Trio ( you get to do a mixed choice among what they got ) and for entrees we ordered the Parrillada for 2 (Mixed Grilled Meats) comes with 2 sides choice  and Bife de Chorizo (Ribeye) with 1 side choice. We also ordered a Sangria Pitcher made by Ariel (Co-Owner) behind the Bar tending to it and also assisting guest rooms n the floor. The sangria was great, refreshing and flavorful with just enough booze to make it pleasant and enjoyable as we wait for the entrees. Entrees came in and the staff was sensitive enough to provide us with enough Chimichurri Sauces for the table, which is an Argentinian sauce that pairs excellent with anything but specially with meats. Throughout the meal the staffed check up on us and we never felt like we need to call or server for lack of attention or service needed to the table. We finally ended the meal with the namesake drink of the place and traditional drink of some south American countries Mate. They served it in this iconic genuine containers with the leaves inside and a metal straw, you can either drink it hot or cold (we ordered hot)  and you serve your level or option if sugar is desired.  So it was pleasant and helped to end our experience here the traditional way Argentinians do by drinking Mate among family and friends. In the bathrooms they have this interesting way to dispense small shots of listerine to wash up your mouth after the meal (Great when on a date or overall anytime!), again this shows the attention to details this owners have to their patrons, its not asked for or required but its provided as an added courtesy to the guest. We thanked Ariel for the meal and he gave us a brief history of the place and invited us to come back again, which we certainly will do so. I give this spot 6 stars for great food but above and beyond services.

On a cold Friday evening my boyfriend and I were greeted by a warm staff in a warm and cozy room. We were informed on the specials of the day and given bread with a DELICIOUS chimichurri sauce, as well as an eggplant spread, which was also good. We started off with 2 red sangria's and 2 empanadas (one beef and one ham & cheese). The 2 empanadas were perfect for sharing as an appetizer and they were VERY good! The dough was perfectly cooked, flaky, and delightful. I didn't care for the red sangria at all, neither did my boyfriend, but he decided he'd take one for the team and drink both of them. I asked for the cocktail menu and the staff noticed that my sangria glass was still full. I did express that I did not care for it when they asked me and they kindly did not charge us for it at the end of the meal. After my bf finished off both sangria's, he had a wonderful glass of Malbec. For my main meal I had the skirt steak and yucca mash. BOTH were out of this world!!!!!! Especially after I smeared several spoon fulls of their chimichurri sauce all over my perfectly cooked, melt in my mouth, steak. BELIEVE the hype on their yucca mash people!!!! BELIEVE...... My sweetie had their steak "special" with merlot mushrooms, asparagus, and mashed potatoes. He was VERY jealous of my yucca mash after tasting his potato mash. Not that they were bad...., the yucca just has that extra special something going on...I detect cheese, has to be the cheese.... Mmmmmm..... For dessert I had the panna cotta (with a cafe con leche) and it was creamy and delectable (coffee was great too!). My NUMBER ONE suggestion to them though is that they ADD a chocolate dessert to their menu. 9 out of 10 people LOVE chocolate and it is ALWAYS the perfect way to end any meal. My boyfriend didn't have any dessert at all because of the lack of chocolate options. All in all El Mate is a KEEPER for us and a romantic place for any couple to reconnect over great cocktails, wine, and amazing food!
